            <!-- Stemmatics -->
            <note type="stemmatics">OY lists four mss., of which none are historic. All texts are
                  relatively late and without special provenance, so it must be considered
                  unverified. Ryad Atlagh is convinced that it is authentic and has presented his
                  arguments in a paper The Phenomenology of the Perfect Man in The Tāʾiyya of Ibn
                  ʿArabī (unpublished, MIAS Symposium, Oxford 1998). All copies we have seen are
                  attributed to IA (varying in length but at least 400 verses). A line-by-line
                  commentary by Abdullah Bosnevi entitled Qurrat ʿayn al-shuhūd also testifies to
                  its authorship by IA. In light of the importance given by Bosnevi to this poem, it
                  is most likely that the original Tāʾiyya should be considered as an authentic
                  work. Critical edition by Yusuf ‘Awda (Cairo, 2015)</note>
